ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-2 Any errors in this report will be corrected when the final report has been completed. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-3 On August 15, 2001, at approximately 1450 mountain daylight time, a Cessna 172N, N733BW, was substantially damaged following impact with terrain in an uncontrolled descent at Meadow Lake Airport, Peyton, Colorado. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-4 The student pilot, the sole occupant aboard the airplane, was seriously injured. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-5 American Aviation, Inc., of Peyton, Colorado, was operating the airplane under Title 14 CFR Part 91. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-6 Visual meteorological conditions prevailed for the local solo instructional flight that originated approximately 35 minutes before the accident. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-7 No flight plan had been filed. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-8 The student was flying his third solo flight when he impacted terrain near the approach end to runway 33. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-9 The airplane had wrinkles in the fuselage. 
ntsb4121txt-1-5-5-0-10 The student's instructor reported that the winds at the time of the accident were approximately 310 to 320 degrees at 10 knots. 
